{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}} '''Blasius of Parma''' ('''Biagio Pelacani da Parma''') (c. 1365 – 1416) was an Italian philosopher, mathematician and astrologer.<ref>Schmidt–Skinner, p. 809.</ref> He popularised English and French philosophical work in Italy, where he associated both with scholastics and with early [[Renaissance humanist]]s.<ref name="Concise Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy">{{cite book|title=Concise Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-bWxJ9IVsAcC&pg=PA91|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=2000|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-0-415-22364-5|page=91}}</ref>
He was professor of mathematics at the [[University of Padua]], where he taught from 1382 to 1388; he taught also at the [[University of Pavia]] (1374? to 1378, and again 1389 to 1407), and the [[University of Bologna]] (1389 to 1382).<ref>{{cite book|author=David C. Lindberg|title=Science in the Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lOCriv4rSCUC&pg=PA140|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=15 March 1980|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|isbn=978-0-226-48233-0|page=140}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Christopher Kleinhenz|title=Medieval Italy: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1piMMqjAf1MC&pg=PA81|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-93930-0|page=81}}</ref> His students included [[Vittorino da Feltre]].<ref>Schmitt–Skinner p. 840; [https://books.google.com/books?id=jJnyxg3xxTEC&pg=PA840 Google Books].</ref>
==Works== Blasius around 1390 wrote a work on [[Perspective (graphical)|perspective]]; it drew on [[Alhacen]], [[John Pecham]], and [[Witelo]].<ref>{{cite book|author=David C. Lindberg|title=Roger Bacon and the Origins of Perspectiva in the Middle Ages: A Critical Edition and English Translation of Bacon's Perspectiva, with Introduction and Notes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jSPHMKbjYkQC&pg=PR98|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=31 October 1996|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-823992-5|page=xcviii}}</ref> [[Filippo Brunelleschi]] may have known of the work of Blasius through [[Giovanni dell'Abbaco]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Mario Lucertini|author2=Ana Millàn Gasca|author3=Fernando Nicolò|title=Technological Concepts and Mathematical Models in the Evolution of Modern Engineering Systems: Controlling, Managing, Organizing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YISIUycS4HgC&pg=PA6|accessdate=3 August 2012|date=22 January 2004|publisher=[[Birkhäuser]]|isbn=978-3-7643-6940-8|page=6}}</ref>
His ''Tractatus de Ponderibus'' was based on Oxford theories on [[Classical mechanics|laws of motion]] taken up from the [[statics]] of [[Jordanus Nemorarius]], and introduced them into Italy.<ref>[[A. C. Crombie]], ''Medieval and Early Modern Science'' vol. II (1959), p. 101.</ref> He disagreed with the views of [[Thomas Bradwardine]] on [[Proportionality (mathematics)|proportion]], and gave a proof of the [[mean speed theorem]]. He also wrote on the natural philosophy of [[Aristotle]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Brian Lawn|title=Rise and Decline of the Scholastic Quaestio Disputata: With Special Emphasis on Its Use in the Teaching of Medicine and Science|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NF6EZFkfo9QC&pg=PA59|accessdate=3 August 2012|year=1993|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-09740-7|page=59}}</ref>
==Modern editions== * Blaise de Parme, ''Questiones super tractatus logice magistri Petri Hispani'', Paris: Vrin, 2001. * Blaise de Parme, ''Quaestiones circa tractatum proportionum magistri Thome Braduardini'', Paris: Vrin, 2006. * Blaise de Parme, ''Questiones super perspectiva communi'', Paris: Vrin, 2009.
